# Kubernetes / EKS Manual Deployment Guide

This guide is intentionally written for manual deployment by a DevOps engineer.

- No bash deployment scripts
- No helper automation
- No loop-based bulk rollout commands
- Explicit per-service image, rollout, and verification steps

This repository currently provides the application code and container build files. Production Kubernetes manifests should be maintained in your infrastructure or GitOps repository. This document tells you exactly what values to use and what to change during deployment.

## Deployment Scope

The platform contains these Kubernetes workloads:

| Workload | Container Port | Public/Private |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `auth-service` | `8081` | Private |
| `employee-service` | `8082` | Private |
| `medicine-catalog-service` | `8083` | Private |
| `inventory-service` | `8084` | Private |
| `procurement-service` | `8085` | Private |
| `sales-distribution-service` | `8086` | Private |
| `production-batch-service` | `8087` | Private |
| `quality-control-service` | `8088` | Private |
| `warehouse-logistics-service` | `8089` | Private |
| `finance-billing-service` | `8090` | Private |
| `frontend` | `80` | Public |

## Prerequisites

- `kubectl` 1.28+
- `helm` 3.x
- Docker
- AWS CLI configured with EKS and ECR access
- Running EKS cluster
- TLS certificate in ACM if using HTTPS ingress
- MongoDB Atlas or another production-grade MongoDB service
- Separate Kubernetes manifests managed by your DevOps or platform repository

