## Step 1 - Configure kubectl for EKS

```bash
aws eks update-kubeconfig \
  --region us-east-1 \
  --name pharma-erp-prod-eks
```

Verify connectivity:

```bash
kubectl get nodes
kubectl get ns
```

## Step 2 - Login to Amazon ECR

Replace the placeholders before running:

- `123456789012` with your AWS account ID
- `us-east-1` with your AWS region

```bash
aws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-1 | docker login \
  --username AWS \
  --password-stdin 123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com
```

## Step 3 - Ensure ECR Repositories Exist

Create each repository manually if it does not already exist:

```bash
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-auth-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-employee-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-medicine-catalog-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-inventory-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-procurement-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-sales-distribution-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-production-batch-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-quality-control-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-warehouse-logistics-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-finance-billing-service --region us-east-1
aws ecr create-repository --repository-name pharma-erp-frontend --region us-east-1
```

If a repository already exists, AWS will return a conflict message. That is safe and expected.

